---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
const API_BASE = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_API_URL || 'https://api.siftersearch.com';
let stats = null;
try {
  const res = await fetch(`${API_BASE}/api/search/stats`);
  if (res.ok) stats = await res.json();
} catch {}
const rc = stats?.religionCounts || {};
const fmt = (n) => n?.toLocaleString() ?? '—';
const fmtM = (n) => {
  if (!n) return '—';
  if (n >= 1_000_000) return (n / 1_000_000).toFixed(1) + ' million';
  if (n >= 1_000) return (n / 1_000).toFixed(1) + 'K';
  return String(n);
};
const fmtShort = (n) => {
  if (!n) return '—';
  if (n >= 1_000_000) return (n / 1_000_000).toFixed(1) + 'M';
  if (n >= 1_000) return (n / 1_000).toFixed(1) + 'K';
  return String(n);
};
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Search & Research Strategy"
  description={`How SifterSearch uses contextual disambiguation, hypothetical question pre-indexing, cross-language semantic search, and prompt caching to make ${fmtM(stats?.totalPassages)} religious text passages searchable with genuine nuance.`}
  activeSection="research-strategy"
>
  <h1>Search &amp; Research Strategy</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">How SifterSearch makes {fmtM(stats?.totalPassages)} passages — across 8 languages and 11 traditions — searchable with the nuance religious texts deserve</p>

  <h2>The Scale of the Problem</h2>

  <p>
    SifterSearch — the search and research intelligence behind
    <a href="https://oceanlibrary.com">OceanLibrary.com</a> — indexes {fmt(stats?.totalDocuments)} religious
    and philosophical texts across three faith traditions:
    {fmt(rc["Baha'i"])} Bahá'í documents, {fmt(rc["Islam"])} Islamic texts (most in Arabic), and a growing collection of
    Buddhist and other writings. Across these traditions, the library contains roughly
    {fmtM(stats?.totalPassages)} individual passages in 8 languages — each a window into centuries of human
    spiritual inquiry.
  </p>
  <p>
    Making those passages genuinely searchable is harder than it sounds. Standard search technology
    was built for the web: short documents, contemporary language, authors who write to be found.
    Religious texts are the opposite. They are dense with allusion, written across millennia in
    translated language, and full of references that only make sense in context. A passage that
    uses "He" might mean God, a prophet, a historical figure, or an archetypal spiritual seeker —
    and the difference matters enormously to anyone doing serious study.
  </p>
  <p>
    This document describes the research strategy SifterSearch uses to close that gap: a layered
    pipeline of AI-assisted enrichment that runs once per passage, at low cost, so that every
    search — no matter how it is phrased, or what language it is phrased in — can find what it
    is actually looking for.
  </p>

